ers date from 1966 to 1973, and span the most creative period in Lonergan's development. Two major themes run through these papers: the primacy of the fourth, existential level of human consciousness, and the significance of historical mindedness with all its implications for culture, hermeneutics, and phenomenological thinking. The theme of conversion makes a grand entrance in 'Theology in Its New Context,' a paper that charted the course for the unfolding of Method in Theology. This new edition makes extensive use of original manuscripts, variants in drafts of the essays, and hand-written corrections.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aEducationxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy. 0aTheology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aDadosky, John , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoran, S.J., Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Pilot 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751157940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487511579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487511579.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  UTP eBook-Package Pilot 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK